<div class="enlarge_html">
    <div class="image_data">
        <span class="credit" aria-label="Image credit">
            
            Simone Golob/Corbis/Getty Images
            
        </span>
    </div>
</div>
   </div>
   <p>It's been a wild week for the financial world. At one point, the U.S. stock market was down <a href="https://www.npr.org/2020/03/09/813619387/dow-dives-1-900-points-nyse-halts-trading-as-stock-indexes-plummet">nearly 20 percent</a> from its peak over fears about the impact of the coronavirus. </p>   <p>We explain how to ride out a stock market crash. And how to grow a nice nest egg and avoid that four-letter word that starts with F — fees. Those can actually do more damage over time than a market downturn.</p>   <p>Here's what to remember:</p>   <p><strong>1. Don't sell stocks when the market tanks.</strong></p>   <div id="res814158205" class="bucketwrap internallink insettwocolumn inset2col ">
            <div class="bucket img">
                  <a id="featuredStackSquareImage676160245" href="https://www.npr.org/2018/12/12/676160245/should-you-pay-for-financial-advice"  data-metrics='{"category":"Story to Story","action":"Click Internal Link","label":"https:\/\/www.npr.org\/2018\/12\/12\/676160245\/should-you-pay-for-financial-advice"}' ><img src="https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2018/12/15/gettyimages-494330247_sq-507287bdd2eafb8b3e765f19d180670b4aee0981-s100-c15.jpg" data-original="https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2018/12/15/gettyimages-494330247_sq-507287bdd2eafb8b3e765f19d180670b4aee0981-s100.jpg" class="img lazyOnLoad"  alt="Should You Pay For Financial Advice?" /></a>         <div class="bucketblock">
                        <h3><a href="https://www.npr.org/2018/12/12/676160245/should-you-pay-for-financial-advice"  data-metrics='{"category":"Story to Story","action":"Click Internal Link","label":"https:\/\/www.npr.org\/2018\/12\/12\/676160245\/should-you-pay-for-financial-advice"}' >Should You Pay For Financial Advice?</a></h3>
         </div>
         
<!-- END CLASS="BUCKETBLOCK" -->
      </div>
      
<!-- END CLASS="BUCKET IMG" -->
   </div>
   
<!-- END ID="RES814158205" CLASS="BUCKETWRAP INTERNALLINK INSETTWOCOLUMN INSET2COL " -->
   <p>When stocks are in free fall, it's scary. You watch your retirement portfolio drop in value. Try thinking about it like a roller coaster. Those can be scary too, but you only get hurt if you jump off the roller coaster. It's better to hang in there and ride back up when the market recovers.</p>   <p>The problem with selling, is nobody knows when the market will turn around and go roaring back up. So if you sell, your retirement fund can get left in a ruined heap at the bottom after the market recovers.</p>   <aside id="ad-backstage-wrap" aria-label="advertisement">
    

    <div id="ad-backstage-no_topic" class="ad-backstage" data-ad-config='{"network":"\/6735\/","site":{"default":"n6735.NPR","mobile":"n6735.NPRMOBILE"},"zone":"no_topic","targets":{"testserver":"false","isPodcastEpisode":"false","storyId":"676158680","agg":["676529561"]},"location":"backstage","deferred":false,"isBetweenContent":true,"isAggSponsorship":false,"borderClass":""}'></div>

</aside>   <div id="res814300328" class="bucketwrap listtext">
